<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05039e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05039e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05039e"> 39(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> &ldquo;House that Jack built&rdquo;</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Twenty years afterwards I heard old Dominicans of the Minerva, Rome, speaking of the wonderful Fra Thomas Burke, who used to tell the &ldquo;Arabian Nights&rdquo; in felicitous Latin to the novices and Fathers during their recreation hours in the gardens of Santa Maria della Querela. They remembered him as &ldquo;Questo maraviglioso giovane Irlandese&rdquo; (this marvellous Irish youth). <br>&ldquo;I also puzzled them with two Italian versions of &lsquo;<mark>The House that Jack Built</mark>&rdquo;&rsquo; (he tells Canon Burke), &lsquo;one grandly heroic &agrave; la Dante&mdash;&lsquo;Behold the edifice Giovanni constructed&rsquo;&mdash;the other in slang Italian.&rdquo; <small> William J. Fitz-Patrick, <a name="BURKE" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BURKE"><cite title="source">The Life of the Very Rev. Thomas N. Burke</cite></a>, (1885) I, 108</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
